'''Aresas''' ({{lang-grc|Ἀρέσας}}) of [[Lucania]], and probably of [[Crotone]], was the head of the [[Pythagoreanism|Pythagorean]] school, and the sixth head of the school in succession from [[Pythagoras]] himself. [[Diodorus of Aspendus]] was one of his students.<ref>{{cite book | last =Zhmud | first =Leonid | translator-first1=Kevin| translator-last1=Windle | translator-first2=Rosh | translator-last2=Ireland | title =Pythagoras and the Early Pythagoreans| publisher =[[Oxford University Press]] | date =2012 | pages =132 | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=of-ghBD9q1QC | isbn = 9780199289318 | accessdate=2018-01-18}}</ref> He lived around the 4th or 5th century BCE.<ref name="poaw">{{cite book | last =Curnow | first =Trevor| title =The Philosophers of the Ancient World: An A-Z Guide | publisher =A&C Black | date =2006 | pages =38 | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=E82oRzHYLhMC | isbn = 9781849667715 | accessdate=2018-01-18}}</ref>

At some point Aresas had to flee Crotone, from people hostile to Pythagoreanism. He may have been the last head of the school in an unbroken line from Pythagoras; on the other hand Neoplatonist philosopher [[Iamblichus]] mentions Aresas as having "re-established" the school, implying a direct lineage might have been broken.<ref name="poaw"/>

Some attribute to Aresas a work "about Human Nature," of which a fragment is preserved by [[Stobaeus]];<ref>[[Stobaeus]], ''Eclogues'' i. p. 847, ed. Heeren</ref> but others suppose it to have been written by the Pythagorean philosopher [[Aesara]].

Some sources conflate Aresas with an "Aresandrus of Lucania", though this "Aresandrus" is otherwise unknown, and modern scholars consider this an error.<ref name="poaw"/><ref>{{cite book | last =Horky | first =Philip Sidney | title =Plato and Pythagoreanism | publisher =[[Oxford University Press]] | date =2016 | pages =128 | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=EXkRDAAAQBAJ | isbn = 9780190465704| accessdate=2018-01-18}}</ref>

