{{See also|Two truths doctrine#East Asian Buddhism|l1=Two truths doctrine}}

''Essence'' is Absolute Reality, the fundamental "cause" or origin, while ''Function'' is manifest or relative reality, the discernible effects or manifestations of ''Essence''.{{sfn|Muller|2005}}{{dead link|date=July 2017}} ''Essence-Function'' describes the interplay between the two: although Absolute Reality is the ultimate reality, the relative reality nevertheless also exists, as is evident from concrete reality. The relationship between these two realms is espressed in such schemata as the [[Five Ranks]]{{sfn|Kasulis|2003|p=29}} and the [[Ten Bulls|Oxherding Pictures]]. Various terms are used for "absolute" and "relative".{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005-A}}

The tree forms a metaphor for ''Essence-Function'', with the roots being ''Essence'' and the branches being ''Function''.{{sfn|Muller|2005}}{{dead link|date=July 2017}} According to Muller "the most important application of t'i-yung thought [...] is to the human being, where the human mind is seen as "essence," and one's words, thoughts and actions are seen as "function."{{sfn|Muller|1999|p=4}}

According to Sung-bae Park the concept of ''essence-function'' is used by East Asian Buddhists "to show a non-dualistic and non-discriminate nature in their [[Kensho|enlightenment experience]]," but does not exclude notions of subjectivity and objectivity.{{sfn|Park|1983|p=147}} According to Sung-bae Park, the terms "essence" and "function" can also be rendered as "body" and "the body's functions," which is a more personal and less abstract expression of nonduality.{{sfn|Park|2009|p=11}}

==Origins and application of the concept==

===China===
The t'i-yung developed in the [[Cao Wei|Wei]] (220–265) – [[Jin dynasty (265–420)|Chin]] (265–420) period of Chinese history, when "Unification of the [[Three teachings|Three Teachings]]" ideology was domimant, striving for a theoretical reconciliation of [[Confucianism]], [[Daoism]], and [[Buddhism]]. The t'i-yung concept was first known as ''pen-mo'' ("primary-last" or "primary-subordinate"), and developed into t'i-yung. In the initial development of the theory, "thinkers considered one of the three philosophies as 'the primary' or 't'i' and the others as 'the last' or 'yung,' insisting that their own philosophy was superior to the others."{{sfn|Kim|2004|p=139}} However, although the theory was used to arrange the three teachings hierarchically, it also confirmed their inner unity.{{sfn|Kim|2004|pp=139–144}}

The concept developed with [[Chinese Buddhism|the introduction of Buddhism in China]], adapting Buddhist philosophy to a Chinese frame of reference. One of the core [[Madhyamaka]] Buddhist doctrines is the [[Two Truths doctrine]], which says that there is a relative truth and an ultimate truth. In Madhyamaka the two truths are two ''epistemological truths'': two different ways to look at reality. Phenomenal reality is relative real or true: one can make factual statements about concrete or manifest reality, but those statements have a relative trueness, since everything that exists changes, and is bound to dissolve again. Ultimately everything is empty, [[sunyata]], of an underlying unchanging essence.{{sfn|Garfield|2002|p=91}} Sunyata itself is also "empty," 'the emptiness of emptiness', which means that ''sunyata'' itself does not constitute a higher or ultimate "essence" or "reality.{{sfn|Garfield|2002|p=38–39}}{{sfn|Siderits|2003}}{{refn|group=note|See also [http://emptinessteachings.com/2014/09/11/the-two-truths-of-buddhism-and-the-emptiness-of-emptiness/ Susan Kahn, ''The Two Truths of Buddhism and The Emptiness of Emptiness'']}} The [[Prajnaparamita|Prajnaparamita-sutras]]  and [[Madhyamaka]] emphasized the non-duality of form and emptiness: form is emptiness, emptiness is form, as the [[heart sutra]] says.{{sfn|Liang-Chieh|1986|p=9}} 

When Buddhism was introduced to China, the two truths doctrine was a point of confusion. Chinese thinking took this to refer to two ''ontological truths'': reality exists of two levels, a relative level and an absolute level.{{sfn|Lai|2003|p=11}} The doctrines of [[Buddha-nature]] and [[Sunyata]] were understood as akin to [[Tao|Dao]] and the Taoist non-being.{{sfn|Lai|2003|p=8}}  It took the Chinese world several centuries to realize that sunyata has another meaning.{{sfn|Lai|2003}}

Based on their understanding of the [[Mahayana Mahaparinirvana Sutra]] the Chinese supposed that the teaching of the Buddha-nature was, as stated by that sutra, the final Buddhist teaching, and that there is an essential truth above sunyata and the two truths. The idea that ultimate reality is present within the daily world of relative reality melded well with Chinese culture, which emphasized the mundane world and society. But this does not tell how the absolute is present in the relative world:
{{quote|To deny the duality of samsara and nirvana, as the Perfection of Wisdom does, or to demonstrate logically the error of dichotomizing conceptualization, as [[Nagarjuna]] does, is not to address the question of the relationship between samsara and nirvana -or, in more philosophical terms, between phenomenal and ultimate reality [...] What, then, is the relationship between these two realms?{{sfn|Liang-Chieh|1986|p=9}}}}

The notions appear already in the ''[[Doctrine of the Mean|Zhongyong]]'' (''Doctrine of the Mean'') attributed to [[Zi Si]] (481–402 BCE), the grandson of [[Confucius]]. The first philosopher to systematically use the ti-yong schema was [[Wang Bi]] (226–249) in his commentary to [[Daodejing]], chapter 22, when he discussed the [[metaphysics|metaphysical]] relation between non-being (''wu'') and being (''you''). Subsequently, the notion has been borrowed from the [[Neo-Daoist]] philosophy to other schools of Chinese philosophy, including [[Huayan school|Hua-yen]] and other schools of Buddhism, and [[Neo-Confucianism]] of [[Cheng Yi (philosopher)|Cheng Yi]] and [[Zhu Xi]], and served as a basic tool of interpretation. With these schools it has travelled to Korea, Japan and Vietnam, and has been developed there.

The ''[[Awakening of Mahayana Faith]]'', a key text in Chinese Buddhism, also employs ''Essence-Function''. Although attributed to [[Aśvaghoṣa]] (?80-?150 CE), and traditionally thought to have been translated [[Paramartha]] (499–569),{{sfn|Tarocco|2008}} in 553, many modern scholars now opine that it was actually composed by Paramartha or one of his students.{{sfn|Grosnick|1989}}

The concept was employed by Confucian reformers of the [[Self-Strengthening Movement]] at the end of the [[Qing dynasty]]'s (1644 to 1912) rule in China, in the phrase "Chinese learning for essence, Western learning for application".{{refn|group=note|({{zh|t=中學為體，西學為用|s=中学为体，西学为用|p= zhōng xué wéi tǐ, xī xué wéi yòng}}}} The belief was that China should maintain its own Confucian style of learning to keep the "essence" of society, while at the same time using Western learning for "practical application" in developing its infrastructure and economy.{{sfn|Spence|1999|pp=225–226}}

===Korean Buddhism===
''Essence-Function'' is an essential element in the philosophy of [[Wonhyo]] (617–686 CE).{{sfn|Muller|1995|pp=33–48}} Wonhyo developed t'i-yung theory into its most influential form in his commentary on the ''Ta ch'eng ch'i hsin lun'' (''Treatise on the Awakening of Mahayana Faith''). This scripture proclaims the non-duality of the phenomenal or mundane world and the ''[[tathagata-garbha]]''.{{sfn|Kim|2004|p=163}} Wonhyo saw the ''Treatise'''s treatment of ''t'i-yung'' as a way of harmonizing the thought of Madhyamika and Yogacara. For Wonhyo, ''t'i'' corresponds to Madhyamika's ultimate truth and ''yung'' to its conventional truth, and these, in turn, are the two gates of Yogacara's one-mind.{{sfn|Kim|2004|pp=164–166}}

[[Chinul]] (1158–1210) and [[Kihwa]] (1376–1433) also employ and develop this idea of Essence-Function in their writings in particular ways.{{sfn|Muller|1995}} [[Wonch'uk]] (613–696) employed the conceptual and analytical tool, Essence-Function, as an exegetical, hermeneutical and syncretic device.

