{{Infobox philosopher | region = [[Western philosophy]] | era = [[20th-century philosophy]] | name = Marvin Farber | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1901|12|14}} | birth_place = [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[New York (state)|New York]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1980|11|24|1901|12|14}} | death_place = [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]] | nationality = American | institutions = [[University of Buffalo]] | alma_mater = | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = [[Edmund Husserl]], [[Martin Heidegger]], [[Heinrich Rickert]], [[Ernst Zermelo]] | doctoral_students = | notable_students = [[Wilfrid Sellars]] | school_tradition = [[Phenomenology (philosophy)|Phenomenology]] | main_interests = [[Ontology]] | notable_ideas = | influences = | influenced = }} '''Marvin Farber''' (December 14, 1901 – November 24, 1980) was an [[United States|American]] [[philosopher]] and educator.
==Early life and education== He was born in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[New York (state)|New York]] to [[Jewish]] parents Simon and Matilda (Goldstein) Farber.<ref name= "obit journal">{{cite journal| title= Obituary: Marvin Farber (1901-1980)| first1= Kah Kyung| last1= Cho | first2= Lynn E.| last2= Rose| journal= Philosophy and Phenomenological Research| volume= 42| number= 1 |date= September 1981| pages= 1–4| publisher= International Phenomenological Society| jstor= 2107539 }}</ref> He was the second oldest of their 14 children.<ref name= "obit journal" /> One of his brothers was pathologist and cancer researcher [[Sidney Farber]].
Initially a music student at the [[University of Buffalo]], but he transferred in 1920 to [[Harvard University]], graduating ''summa cum laude'' with his bachelor's degree in philosophy in 1922.<ref name= BioNote>{{cite web| url= http://libweb1.lib.buffalo.edu:8080/findingaids/view?docId=ead/archives/ubar_0768.xml | title= Biographical Note in Finding Aid for the Marvin Farber Papers, Professor of Philosophy and Phenomenology, circa 1920-1980: 22/5F/768| website= Buffalo.edu| publisher= State University of New York at Buffalo| access-date= May 8, 2017}}</ref> He earned his Ph.D. in 1925 at Harvard.<ref name= BioNote /><ref name= "obit journal" /> He also attended German universities of [[University of Berlin|Berlin]], [[University of Heidelberg|Heidelberg]], and [[University of Freiburg|Freiburg]], studying under [[Edmund Husserl]], [[Martin Heidegger]], [[Heinrich Rickert]], and [[Ernst Zermelo]], among others.<ref name= BioNote />
==Career== Farber taught for a year at [[Ohio State University]] between his studies in Germany.<ref name= "obit journal" /> He then taught at his initial alma mater, the [[University at Buffalo]], from 1927-1961 and 1964-1974;<ref name= BioNote /> during the interim, he was Chairman of the Department of Philosophy at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name= "obit journal" /> After his first year at University of Buffalo, he was appointed Assistant Professor.<ref name= "obit journal" /> He founded the journal ''Philosophy and Phenomenological Research'' in 1940 and was its editor until 1980. He was Chairman of the Department of Philosophy from 1937 to 1961. He was designated [[Professor Emeritus]] in 1974 and retired in 1977.<ref name= BioNote />
==Personal life and demise== He died in [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]] after months of serious illness.<ref name= "obit journal" /> He was survived by his loving wife Lorraine and three children, Lawrence, Roger and Carol.
==Honors and awards== * [[Guggenheim Fellowship]], 1944–45<ref name= BioNote /> * Docteur de l'[[Lille University of Science and Technology|Universitė de Lille]], 1955<ref name= "obit journal" /> * President, [[American Philosophical Association]] (Eastern Division), 1963<ref name= "obit journal" />
==Bibliography== * ''[[Naturalism (philosophy)|Naturalism]] and [[Subjectivism]]'', 1959 {{ISBN|0-87395-036-4}} * ''[[Phenomenology (philosophy)|Phenomenology]] and Existence: Toward a Philosophy within Nature'', 1967. {{ISBN|0-06-131295-9}} * ''The Search for an Alternative: Philosophical Perspectives of Subjectivism and [[Marxism]]'', 1984. {{ISBN|0-8122-7921-2}} * ''The Foundation of Phenomenology: [[Edmund Husserl]] and the Quest for a Rigorous Science of Philosophy'', 2006. {{ISBN|0-202-30853-7}}
