{{Infobox book | name = Modern Man in Search of a Soul | title_orig = | translator = Carl F. Baynes with William Stanley Dell | image = Modern Man in Search of a Soul.jpg | caption = | author = Carl Jung | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = German, English | series = | subject = Psychology | genre = | published = 1933 [[Charles Kegan Paul|Kegan Paul, Trench, Trubner and Co, London]] (English) | media_type = Print | pages = 282 (1st edition) | isbn = 0-15-661206-2 | isbn_note = (Mariner Books edition) | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Modern Man in Search of a Soul''''' is a book of psychological essays written by Swiss psychologist [[Carl Jung]].
==Background== In the years preceding this publication Jung had experienced several dramatic shifts. After the Bugishu Psychological Expedition throughout Africa with [[George Beckwith (Carl Jung associate)|George Beckwith]], Jung returned to [[Zurich]] and focused on the lecture format of his English seminars at the Psychological Club - eventually attracting a new group of international followers.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bair |first=Deirdre |title=Jung: A Biography |year=2003 |publisher=Little, Brown and Company |location=New York |isbn=0-316-15938-7 |page=358}}</ref> In addition to expanding his academic following, Jung's professional psychiatric practice also rapidly grew taking on notable patients like [[Mary Foote]] and [[Thornton Wilder]]. During this period in Zurich Jung struck up a friendship with [[Wolfgang Ernst Pauli]].
In the translators' preface Carl F. Baynes provides some background to the material: {{Quotation|With one exception, all the essays which make up this volume have been delivered as lectures. The German texts of four of them have been brought out in separate publications and the others are to be found in a volume [Seelenprobleme der Gegenwart] together with several other essays which have already appeared in English.<ref>{{cite book |last=Jung |first=Carl |title=Modern Man in Search of a Soul |year=1933 |publisher=Harvest |location=New York |isbn=0-15-661206-2 |page=translators' preface}}</ref>}}
Jung's various presentations to the Psychological Club in Zurich in this period, notably his 1932 seminar on [[Kundalini]] yoga, have been widely regarded as a milestone in the psychological understanding of [[eastern philosophy|Eastern thought]]. Kundalini yoga presented Jung with a model for the development of higher consciousness, and he interpreted its symbols in terms of the process of [[individuation]].<ref name="Jung">Princeton University Press, Book description to C. G. Jung - "The Psychology of Kundalini Yoga", 1999</ref>
==Summary== The writing covers a broad array of subjects such as [[gnosticism]], [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|theosophy]], [[Eastern philosophy]] and [[spirituality]] in general. The first part of the book deals with [[Dream interpretation#Jung|dream analysis]] in its practical application, the problems and aims of modern [[psychotherapy]], and also his own theory of [[psychological types]]. The middle section addresses Jung's beliefs about the stages of life and [[Archaic man]]. He also contrasts his own theories with those of [[Sigmund Freud]].
In the latter parts of the book Jung discusses [[Psychoanalytic literary criticism|psychology and literature]] and devotes a chapter to basic postulates of [[analytical psychology]]. The last two chapters are devoted to the spiritual problem of modern man in [[aftermath of World War I]]. He compares it to the flowering of gnosticism in the 2nd century and investigates how psychotherapists are like the [[clergy]].
